block content
  h2 File System
  p This lesson should take you 1 hour to complete. It will teach you some core commands that you can use to interact with the file system like ls, pwd, cd, mkdir, rm, and mv.

  p You will also hear a lot about specific folders on the Linux system and what they are used for but you don't need to memorize all those folders or even understand them all right now.

  h2 Video - 30 min
  p
    iframe(width="1120",height="630", src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/BNL3qBN9pP0", title="YouTube video player", frameborder="0", allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" ,allowfullscreen)

  h2 Projects - 30 min
  ol
    li How can you tell what type of file each item is when you run
      span.terminal ls -l
    li What does the ~ mean on the file system?
    li What is the / folder?
    li What does pwd stand for?
    li What does cd stand for?
    li What does ls stand for?
    li What is the difference between an absolute file path and a relative file path?
    li What command would you use to see the contents of a file located at ~/things.txt
    li What its the purpose of the /etc folder?
    li How can you create multiple levels of folders at once?
    li How to you remove a folder?
    li How can you use mv to rename a folder called first to be named second.

  h2 Nice Job!
  p You now know the basics of the Linux file system!
